                       A Voice in the Night. <br>
<br>
<br>
My body was telling me it was late, demanding from me a respite from the fatigue induced aches I had forced upon my self. In recent days I had wandered Luclin in melancholy solitude seeking whatever battle I could find, offering my sword and gifts to whoever needed them. Penance for my sins. <br>
<br>
I rarely sleep anymore. The dreams of yesterday are too much for my battered psyche. I am beginning to think I am damaged beyond all hope. Too many crimes for my short life. Too many acts I can never undo. I used to understand the rage, now it leaves me confused and empty, so terribly empty. I have echoes in my mind of a time before, a time when I was filled with hope and light. What remains of my heart aches for the girl I once was. The sound of laughter close by me takes me back again. I remember all that I have lost. <br>
<br>
I had a family once. <br>
<br>
I grew up in a strong house. My parents served the lightbearer well. They raised me with love and taught me honor. I faced the world sure that I could make a difference. <br>
<br>
It was an arrogant and hollow belief. <br>
<br>
Those that I loved were ripped from my life one by one. Friends, lovers and finally one terrible day my family as well. <br>
<br>
I was home in North Freeport after a painful and nearly fatal journey across Norrath. My body was battered and my spirit all but broken. I was bedridden for almost a week healing from my physical injuries. My mother said it was a miracle I had made it home alive. Looking back I believe it to be no more than a cruel cosmic joke. Some strange fate of mine to be restored and then taken down layer by layer in unimaginably painful ways. It is a cycle that will not seem to end. <br>
<br>
My mother tended to my recovery with love. It was her way and I took refuge in her warmth. She waited with patience born of love for me to tell my story. Gently removing the walls I had erected around my self, walls I had placed in an effort to protect myself from the anguish of my losses. I remember our last conversation well. If I concentrate I can still hear her voice, the gentle melody of her love as she soothed my broken heart. <br>
<br>
There is nothing I wouldn't give to hear that again, to feel that again, Marr, to know I was loved and cared for. I miss her so deeply my marrow aches with the loss. <br>
<br>
It's a futile wish. She is gone. They all are. It's fates cruelty that I did not follow. They were killed. I lived, again. <br>
<br>
I have to concentrate to remember their living faces, but I only need close my eyes to remember their deaths. <br>
<br>
I fought so hard against the invaders. I gave everything I had to the fight, screaming at my sister to run for help. Dodging blow after blow, keeping myself between the militia and my younger brothers and sister. My mother and father fighting by my side, the grim looks upon their faces as they took the fight to the invaders. It was then I was lifted into the air and thrown hard to the ground. The air left my lungs in a rush and my vision grayed out. <br>
<br>
When my vision cleared I was on my knees, someone's hand fisted in my hair holding me upright. I felt cold steel against my throat and I was sure my death was near. Fate had another plan for me. <br>
<br>
I watched as my family was slaughtered. Seven times over I watched someone I loved more than my own life murdered. I screamed my fury and pain until my voice left me. <br>
<br>
The murderers of my family laughed. <br>
<br>
The man holding me removed his blade from my throat and plunged it into my shoulder. I heard them leave as I lay there bleeding, my blood mixing with the blood of my family. My living eyes locked on the dead. <br>
<br>
I survived to bury my family. I honored them during the burial rites with all the love I had for them. Once the ceremony ended I turned and walked away from my home. I did not look back. <br>
<br>
I died that day. <br>
<br>
The next I was reborn as vengeance. My existence became one of hate. I would hunt those that had wronged me to the last man. They would know suffering and fear. I gave my self to rage and became death. <br>
<br>
I traveled to Queynos and then Halas. I lived among the Barbarian warriors in that frozen city for 5 seasons learning from them everything I could. When I began my journey again I was a formidable foe. It was time to head home and avenge my family. <br>
<br>
I moved in the shadows as if I had been born to them. I was a silent predator; the closer to Freeport I came the more my bloodlust grew. I took the first of my victims in the West Commonlands. I did not care who the man was, only that he wore the mark of the militia. The mark of death. <br>
<br>
He was no more than a boy, but he was serving those that had slaughtered my family. He feared me. I held absolute power over him and it felt good. I asked him if he knew why he was going to die. He did not. He knew not of my family nor my house. I explained to him. One wound for each victim. I let his agonized cries wash over me as I rejoiced in his pain. I placed my dagger over his heart and said to him, &quot;This one is for Nishal.&quot;  Slowly I forced my weapon into his flesh, through bone and stilled his heart with a viscous twist of my blade. I left his body for the animals to feast upon and continued toward Freeport. <br>
<br>
I left a trail of death behind me. My rage grew with every kill. I was drunk on the power I held over my enemy. It was good, it was right and I would not stop until the whole of them were rotting in the sun. Days turned into weeks and I lost count of my victims. The last of my humanity had fled the remnants of my soul and I was free of conscience. I became legend in the streets of Freeport, people feared me though they knew me not. I had but one name to them. Death. <br>
<br>
I was stalking a Sargent in the East Commonlands when the past found me. I crested a hill and came face to face with a man I had once known. Someone I was sure was dead. He looked at me in shock at first and then his eyes warmed as recognition dawned on him. His face split with an open smile as he grasped my forearms. I took an involuntary step backward at his touch. No one had touched me in years. Not like that. <br>
<br>
I'd had my share of men. Used them to satisfy my needs, but never let them touch me with affection. I did not want nor need their love. I had no use for it in my life. I chose men who wanted nothing more than the carnal pleasures I offered. I was a fierce warrior and a feral lover. <br>
<br>
This man, Hatath, who stood before me, was from a long forgotten past. I had loved him once. The memory of those times came rushing back to me as he said my name. <br>
<br>
&quot;Nishal.&quot;<br>
<br>
I shook my head and took another step back, almost satisfied at the hurt confusion that crossed his face. &quot;You've mistaken me for someone else.&quot; I said curtly before fleeing the other direction. To my great relief he did not follow. <br>
<br>
I ran to my refuge, not stopping nor looking back. I had never thought I would see anyone from my past, least of all Hatath. One safely inside I curled myself into a corner. Alone in the darkness I tried to banish the memories that had surfaced. <br>
<br>
I remembered the day he died. The day I thought he died. That horrifying Day in Katta. I remembered the look on his face as he fell. I remembered my own scream of vain denial as he disappeared from view and my companions bodily holding me back, wrestling me in the other direction and forcing me to flee our pursuers.  <br>
<br>
I had believed him dead all these years. Unwanted guilt washed over me from my reawakened conscience. I had left him alone and broken to the tender mercies of the enemy. Within my perverse nature a voice hoped he would be the one to finally end my wretched existence one I had completed my mission. A louder voice fervently wished to never see him again. He was a threat to the mission, a threat to the ebony I had become. A threat because I could so clearly remember the love I had for him. Nishal was dead. In her place The Mistress of Death had arisen. Nishal was dead, she had to be for I could not afford the price of her compassion. <br>
<br>
My sleep that night was plagued with the memories of before. My nightmares were the dreams that most longed for. I dreamed of my family and friends, feeling in my subconscious the joy of times passed. In my sleep love washed me clean and I saw a future filled with hope. In my dreams that night Nishal lived once more. <br>
<br>
I awoke the next morning confused and alone. Emotions long dormant were at war within me. A new ache had developed deep within. The creature I had become did not understand and used her formidable will to wipe my mind clean of the unwanted feelings. I had work to do. I had a Sargent to kill. <br>
<br>
This man was to die differently from the rest. This man I knew. He was there that night. It was his face I had seen on the others I had killed. This was the man who drawn his blade across my mother's throat.<br>
<br>
