An involuntary sigh escaped me as I lay my head against the smooth stone wall of the Nexus. Weary resignation clouded my heart as my mind once again bore me to my terrible past. <br>
<br>
I hunted Sargent Slate for two full days before I picked up his trail again. The hunt had become more difficult because of the phantom trailing me. I was certain my mind was crumbling. Living the way I had, it was inevitable. I was living, breathing madness; it was only a matter of time before it consumed me. <br>
<br>
On the fringe of my sight a figure in crimson and gray followed me. Hatath. I allowed him to follow, knowing what would be done should he interfere. The chill had reclaimed my heart and death would not be moved for him. <br>
<br>
Hatath had died and in my fragmented delusion I could keep him dead. This man following me was a stranger. I could kill a stranger if need be. <br>
<br>
I crouched beneath the brush along a seldom-traveled road. The Sargent would be passing soon. It was almost time. <br>
<br>
&quot;You've changed.&quot;<br>
<br>
I whirled around my blade drawn ready to gut the man behind me, but Hatath was on me with inhuman speed. I had not even formed my cry of rage when his hand clamped painfully against my mouth and nose severed it. I fought him with everything I had to no avail, my hate, pain and fury were impotent. The ice in my vein would not save me. My lungs spasmd with the pain of death and I stilled. My gaze locked on his. It was his right to gain retribution against me. <br>
<br>
The victory I expected to see in his face was not there. <br>
<br>
What I saw was grief and in the fading lights of my life a single tear. <br>
