“How did we come to this?”<br>
<br>
I opened my eyes to see a face full of pity staring back at me. Hatath was as I remembered him. His face open and compassionate; his eyes full of the love he held for me.  To the person I had become it was a revolting sight. <br>
<br>
“You should have killed me.” I said coolly as I rose from his bed. I stood before this man, my body naked, but my soul was cloaked in fury. “I would not have hesitated to kill you and I wouldn’t recommend turning your back on me anytime soon.” My voice held an arrogance I did not feel.<br>
<br>
No, indeed, just beneath my rage, other emotions lurked. Just under the mask of vengeance I wore, the person I once was fought to escape the hatred. The person who loved this man with every bit of light Marr had given her was working her way to the surface. She, I, still loved him and at that moment wanted nothing more than to be held by him and cry each tear I had denied for the past six seasons into his shoulder.<br>
<br>
I had hated for so long, the persona of Nishal was foreign to me. She had become a phantom of my fractured memory.  <br>
<br>
“You do not scare me, Nishal.” He said to me. His voice was firm but gentle. I could see he had no fear and it infuriated me. The voice of hate shouted above the voice of love. The two halves of my soul had gone to war, the chaos of it screamed through my nerves. The energy within became frenetic as I paced wildly about. <br>
<br>
“You are a fool!” I hissed, speaking both to Hatath and my self. He just shook his head and remained silent. “What do you want with me? Why bring me here?”<br>
<br>
“I wanted to speak with you.”<br>
<br>
“About what?” I snarled at him. “What do you want to know, Hatath?” His name sounded a slur upon my lips.  <br>
<br>
“What happened to you?”<br>
<br>
“YOU DIED!” <br>
<br>
“I did.” He said gently. <br>
<br>
“Yes! You did! Pavem died, Nali died, MY FAMILY, FAITH, HOPE AND LOVE ALL DIED!” I could feel my body shake with anger. “I was left with NOTHING! NO ONE! So I whored my self to hate. Innoruuk's slut and I bathed in the blood of those I held responsible. AND I LIKED IT!” My breath now came in great gasps as my hysterical rage grew. “I AM a Mistress of Misery, bringer of pain and death. Damned to walk still living of body but long dead of soul because I was unworthy of death's release. I am darkness complete!”<br>
<br>
“I would not be here if that were true.”<br>
<br>
I laughed at him. “You're dead! Go to your GOD and have him count for you my crimes!”<br>
<br>
“Your mother weeps, Nishal.”<br>
<br>
The words shook me to my core. I stood staring at him for a moment before I found my voice again. “My mother is dead, she cannot weep.”<br>
<br>
“I am dead and yet have brought YOU to the brink of death. Your mother most certainly can weep and she does Nish.”<br>
  <br>
My heart was compressed by a mournful weight and I could feel tears make their journey down my cheeks for the first time in nearly six seasons. Then he touched me. His hand gentle upon my face, wiping away my tears. A shuddering breath escaped me as the warmth of him began to thaw the ice in my veins. <br>
<br>
“Tell me how you became this.”<br>
<br>
For the first time since the deaths of my family I felt shame. I lowered my head, unable to meet his eyes and slowly began my story. I did not want to tell him. I did not want to recount my sin, yet the time had come for the telling. My life since I left him in Katta was laid bare for his scrutiny.  A grim confession from a shattered soul. <br>
<br>
The words came forth unbidden. The truth of what I had become explained with every painful and vile detail. When I finished my tale we sat in silence for long minutes. Finally I found the courage to look into his eyes, I found the courage to face the disgust and condemnation he must surely have felt for me. <br>
<br>
For the second time that day, Hatath surprised me. I saw sorrow in him. I saw regret, but no judgement. <br>
<br>
When he spoke his voice was breaking with emotion. “More than anything Nishal, I regret not being with you when you needed me the most. I am so very sorry.”<br>
<br>
I shook my head. “You've no crime here.” My voice was raw and breaking. “I could not save you. I could not protect you, Pavem or Nali.” Tears once again fell upon my face. “I tried so hard for you, for my family, I fought so hard and I still lost. I just don’t understand. I don’t understand Hatath.” My statement was more a plea. I had fought the best I could and still lost everything. I could not have loved them more than I did. I could not have cared for them better than I did and still I lost them. Everything I had to give was not enough to keep them safe. I did not understand how that could be. <br>
<br>
Hatath wrapped his arms around me as he spoke. “I could take you back to that day. You could live it a thousand times and still not save me. You bear no fault for my death or theirs and I love you too much to put you through that day again to prove it to you. You trusted me once, trust me now when I say you did everything you could have done for us. You fought bravely and well, we could not have asked more of you.”<br>
<br>
“Why wasn't it enough?”<br>
<br>
He turned my face to his. “There are evils in this world greater than one can face alone. They hold power that can only be overcome by a host of bright spirits. You have been tested and are still being tested. The shadows are seductive, they've battered you and now offer fallacious solace. They've perverted your pain and led you with entreaties of righteous vengeance.” Hatath sighed. “You cannot continue down this path, that is why I am here now. You have to fight them Nish, if you do not, much more will be lost than just your soul.”<br>
<br>
