<br>
I looked at him, the question clear upon my face. “What do you mean? Surely, I am not so important?&quot;<br>
<br>
“You are, far more than I can say.” He stroked my hair as he spoke. “Think Nishal, when something unjust happened, you were always the first to ask why. You were always the first to take up arms in defense of the wronged. When you were wronged, you stopped asking why and allowed yourself to be led down this path of hatred. They wanted that. Nish, a great shadow rises, even as the followers of light take back what was theirs, the shadow of darkness grows and festers within the hearts of many on this world. Still, it is afraid. Nishal it fears you and people like you. Light and justice shine brightly with in you, though you have been trying to cloak them in darkness. This cannot continue. I cannot tell you more, it is not for me to tell and there is little time left for you here. Please Nishal, trust me, trust the light within you begging to be set free and trust those who will be with you when you wake. Your road will not be easy, but you must take it. Release the anger, your family and friends are well here and they love you so much.” Hatath’s voice cracked with emotion. “I love you, it will always be so. Never will you take a step alone Nishal, not until one worthy in life shall take my place. I promise you that.”<br>
<br>
I wept openly against his shoulder, confusion and loss reigned with in my heart, yet amidst the pain hope sang a gentle lullaby. My eyes and limbs were heavy, but I did not wish to surrender to sleep. I did not wish to leave his comfort so soon. I knew I would not wake alone, the knowledge was without foundation, but still I knew. A family of strangers awaited me, I could almost see them as varied as the lands I had traveled, they were a family, fighting, loving and loosing together. <br>
<br>
I sighed sleepily against Hatath’s shoulder. “I miss you.” I whispered to him as my eyes closed. <br>
<br>
“I miss you too my love, but I am with you always.” I heard him sing into my heart as darkness lay claim to my consciousness. <br>
<br>
All too soon, voices, living voices intruded upon my rest. <br>
<br>
“You say she is not injured?”<br>
<br>
“Nay, she is well.”<br>
<br>
“She does not wake!”<br>
<br>
“She will when she is ready! Now away with thee!”<br>
<br>
I faded into the darkness once more. When next I woke, it was to sunlight warming my face. I felt comfortable, warm and rested for the first time in what felt like ages. I sighed as my body stretched into wakefulness. <br>
<br>
“It's about time!” A firm but gentle voice came from above me. I opened my eyes to see a human man standing above me. “We though you might well sleep another day away.”<br>
<br>
I couldn’t help but smile at the thought. “It seems tempting. It's…”<br>
<br>
“What?” he asked as a small frown of concern creased his mouth. <br>
<br>
I sat up, gathered the blankets around me and shook my head. “Nothing, it's just been a long time since I have slept in a real bed.”<br>
<br>
He chuckled. “I'm sorry, forgive my manners. I should introduce my self. I am Coldarm, my brethren and I found you in the East Commonlands three days ago. We brought you here, to our Guildhall.”<br>
<br>
“Thank you. You have done me a great kindness. I am Nishal.” <br>
<br>
“Please forgive my asking, but we have been curious as to how you came to be in such a state? What happened?”<br>
<br>
I sighed and looked at him for a moment. “Alot.”<br>
<br>
He frowned at me, clearly not satisfied with my answer. I understood, but it was not yet within me to tell my story to the living. So much had changed in my heart so quickly that my mind was in crisis. I needed time to...reflect. “I am sorry for my cryptic reply, but the truth of it is, I myself am not entirely sure. When I have had the time to put all the pieces together I will tell you. I just need time to sort it all out. I’ve only just woken.” I smiled at him but the shadow of memory was settling over my heart. <br>
<br>
“It is I who should apologize. I did not mean to pry.” He rose from his chair. “I will let Aaldari know you have woken. She is most anxious to meet you.” He turned to leave and then stopped. “She is a fine leader and has a noble heart, but, she seems a bit...um...strong...no, that's not the right term...rough around the edges to those that don't know her.”<br>
<br>
“Ah, I understand. Thank you for the...information.” When the door closed behind him, I let out a long breath. “Hatath, where have you seen fit to put me?”<br>
<br>
I had not expected an answer, but received one none the less as his presence whispered through my soul. “Where you need to be.”<br>
<br>
