 <br>
/IC<br>
<br>
I had wandered from the Nexus to Shadow Haven in search of a quiet corner of a quiet inn in which to have a drink. The memories seemed to come to me wanted or not and if I could not quell them perhaps I could dull them with a stout ale. <br>
<br>
The memory of my first days among the Edger's as they called themselves warmed me. It was the closest thing to a home I had felt in many a season. They were good people, and Aaldari, while brash and simply spoken was a woman of great honor. I saw in her eyes pain and trials unspoken, her eyes were much like my own. We spoke at length of many things for we had both been witness to great evil. In her I saw a great leader and possibly for the first time since my family's death, hope. <br>
<br>
She had drawn to her a varied group of people, some born to the light others companions to the darkness. It surprised me to see them all defer to this woman with the same respect. She told me of many other members in her house scattered across the lands of Norrath and Luclin. Some in the house regarded me with a cautious eye but others were welcoming. I shared my story with Aaldari, for if she were to accept me she needed the truth. I was a hunted woman in the lands surrounding Freeport and she deserved to know why. <br>
<br>
“So it was you?” She regarded me with a critical eye. “You were the one laying waste to the militia?”<br>
<br>
“Aye.” <br>
<br>
“You have strength.” She said.<br>
<br>
“I am a murderer. I hid in shadows as a coward.”<br>
<br>
“I’ll not argue with ye about bein a murderer.” She nodded at me. “But...vengeance is a powerful thing. It clouds yer mind an drives ye to things ye wouldn't normally do. I don't see a coward in ye, no, a coward would not have told me what ye have this day. I stand by what I said, ye have strength.”<br>
<br>
I simply lowered my head in acceptance of her words. Though this woman before me lacked formal education she held a wisdom I had only seen in a handful of people before her. “Time will tell if this strength you see will last.”<br>
<br>
“Yer a stubborn wench, I'll tell ye right now!” She laughed at me. “I’m not blind Nishal, ye have a heart born of light. Yeh've been denying it fer too long!” <br>
<br>
“That may be true, but until the day comes that I can see and feel it for myself, the words mean nothing.”<br>
<br>
“Aye,” she nodded, “The road to redemption is a long one indeed. Yeh'll need the strength I see and then some to see it to the end.”  She paused looking at me thoughtfully. “I know more than most what kind o' trials ye face now. Sometimes it feels like yer heart is screaming. I know this, but I can’t advise ye.”<br>
<br>
“I know. The choices are as they always have been. Mine.” I sighed, the weight of what I had done settled around me with fierce oppression. <br>
<br>
“Indeed.”<br>
<br>
I shook the gathering clouds away, for there was still something I had to do before I could truly seek redemption. “I must beg your leave for a few days. There is someone I must meet.”<br>
<br>
Aaldari turned a hard eye on me. “The Tier'Dal.” She said cooly. <br>
<br>
“Yes.” I nodded. “Shadow or Light she takes great risk in meeting me. She has the right to know I will not be back.”<br>
<br>
“I'll not say I understand.” She said finally. “And I dun think I'll persuade ye not to go. Ye will have a companion. Groger will go with ye. Yeh'll not be walking into the den of snakes unprotected.”<br>
<br>
I thought to argue. Looking at this woman I knew that would be a futile endeavor, I would loose...badly. “Very well, I plan to leave at dusk. It is safer for me to travel by night and I would not put Groger to risk being seen with me.”<br>
<br>
“Fair enough. And Nishal, this should be clear, I expect the both o ye ta be returning to us. Understood?”<br>
<br>
I nodded. “Understood.”<br>
<br>
<br>
